3.29	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the following:
1. Property Supply Officer:
For the designated Supply Officer to update/ renew all the PARs/ AREs issued to end-users, and identify the properties issued to retired/ resigned employees/ officials that were not properly turned-over. This would facilitate the identification of PPEs that are missing or not found in the supposed station; and to update the RPCPPE thru the conduct of physical inventory of assets, ensuring to include all new acquisitions of PPEs and those assets that are not yet counted in the report;
2. Municipal Accountant:
To provide updated PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) to the Inventory Committee, including all newly acquired assets;
After the conclusion of activities for One-Time Cleansing, provide for the accounting entries for the recognition of PPEs found at station but not previously recorded, recognition of loss of PPEs, writing-off/ dropping from the books of accounts the remaining balances/ amounts lumped under the unreconciled SL of PPEs, and derecognition of non-existing/ missing PPEs (accomplish Annex D and also refer to Annex E of COA Circular 2020-006 for the entries)
Provide disclosures on PPE in the Notes to FS the total amount of non-existing/ missing PPEs included in the PPE balance, supported with breakdown as to sub-major PPE account group, and PPEs found station which are still needing appraisal, following item 9.0 of the same COA Circular;
3. Inventory Committee members:
To create a strategic Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) detailing the specific assignments /duties of the committee members, cut-off dates, and schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities to be approved by the Municipal Mayor;
To prepare the PIP based from the latest RPCPPE or Inventory Count Form (Annex A) and PPELCs, as coordinated with the Property Unit/ designated Supply Officer and Accounting Unit;
In the event that no RPCPPE was accomplished, prepare the format for Inventory Count Form (ICF) following Annex A, and instruct all offices to provide list of PPEs assigned/ detailed at their stations; and ensure that the inventory taking activities are executed according to the approved PIP; the condition of the PPEs counted shall be clearly indicated in the ICF;
For PPEs that are reported missing/ non-existing, not found in the station, or counted but not yet recorded, follow through with the procedures as enumerated under COA Circular 2020-006; and
With the cooperation of the designated Supply Officer, accomplish Annexes A, B, and C of the same COA Circular.
Lastly, Disposal Committee shall be created pursuant to COA-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2024-1, dated January 30, 2024. This committee shall effect the disposal of PPEs as a result of the One-Time Cleansing of accounts.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the following: 

For the RHU personnel to furnish copy of claims to the Municipal Accountant in order to set up Due from GOCCs account – receivable from PhilHealth. This would aid in the monitoring of claims pending to be paid by PhilHealth; 

For the LGU liaison personnel to inquire from PhilHealth on the deficiencies that they need to address/ submit in order to release the claims from CY 2023; 

For the Municipal Accountant to check and review her records vis-à-vis the bank statements on whether or not she was able to make JEV for all the claims transferred to the RHU accounts; 

For the Municipal Treasurer to make Certification on the Receipt of Claims from PhilHealth via bank transfer in lieu of an Official Receipt to support the JEV as evidence; and 

For the Municipal Accountant to record the receivables from PhilHealth.

We have reiterated our previous recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:
To create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The Inventory Committee shall have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Divisions/Units of the agency.
To instruct the Inventory Committee/Treasury office and Accounting office to reconcile the differences, if any, between the physical inventory report and the general ledger balance of each PPE account; subsequently, the Accountant shall identify if the difference represents PPE that are still existing, no longer existing but with pertinent records, or vice-versa.
To apprise the conduct of annual physical inventory and make updates on the current/ existing inventory reports, and to adhere with the timeline of activities under the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP). The Inventory Committee and accounting shall compare the latest Report on the RPCPPE/Inventory Report with the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs);
To enjoin the Inventory Committee to prepare a list of PPE items which are recorded in the PPELCs but not included in the RPCPPE/Physical Inventory Report as well as PPE items which are included in the RPCPPE but not recorded in the PPELCs;
That after the completion of physical count, for the PPEs classified as non-existing/ missing and of those without available records of accountability, the procedures enumerated under Items 7 and 8 of the same COA Circular for the disposition and derecognition must be done.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the following:
For the RHU personnel to furnish copy of claims to the Municipal Accountant in order to set up Due from GOCCs account – receivable from PhilHealth. This would aid in the monitoring of claims pending to be paid by PhilHealth;
For the LGU liaison personnel to inquire from PhilHealth on the deficiencies that they need to address/ submit in order to release the claims from CY 2023;
For the Municipal Accountant to check and review her records vis-à-vis the bank statements on whether or not she was able to make JEV for all the claims transferred to the RHU accounts;
For the Municipal Treasurer to make Certification on the Receipt of Claims from PhilHealth via bank transfer in lieu of an Official Receipt to support the JEV as evidence; and
For the Municipal Accountant to record the receivables from PhilHealth.

In view of the foregoing we have recommended the following:

Require the Municipal Accountant to identify the existence of the Registry of Public Infrastructure which includes all local road networks implemented by the Municipality prior to the implementation of IPSAS;

Create an Inventory Committee who shall be responsible in the conduct of physical inventory of local road networks funded by the Municipality; 

Require Municipal Engineer to prepare a list of road inventory and its vicinity map for easy identification during and after the physical inventory and;

Ensure that road components (road lot, pavements, drainage and slope, etc.) are indicated in the road network ledger and property cards maintained by the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer.

In view of the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended to Management the following:

To reconcile the records pertaining to the unremitted contributions and loan repayments and to effect immediately the remittance of long overdue accounts, if any; 

To remit intact all the GSIS contributions and loan amortizations on or before the 10th day of the following month to ensure that officials and employees enjoy the GSIS benefits to the maximum and as well as to avoid incurrence of penalties.

With all the foregoing observations, we recommended that the Management to:

       Instruct the BAC Secretariat to carefully observe the proper identification of the contract to be bid and the categorization of the items in the Invitation to Bid in posting at the PhilGEPS;

            Likewise, avoid inclusion of items in the Purchase Request (PR) which incongruous to each other to achieve the most advantageous price and quality in favor of the LGU.

            Submit a written explanation on the noted inconsistencies and deficiencies noted on the above transaction;

          Create Inspection Team with members capable of handling inspection of supplies and materials for check and balance; and

         Record all purchases on drugs and medicines in the books using the Perpetual Inventory Method.
